│ stop({"edit_points": [[1249, 1249,                                          │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.  │
│ Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe crash occurs when the SCEVExpander tries to │
│ compute the difference between two SCEV expressions in                      │
│ `tryToReuseLCSSAPhi`, specifically calling `SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV)`.  │
│ The `ExitSCEV` is a `SCEVCouldNotCompute` object, which cannot be used in   │
│ any SCEV operations. When `getMinusSCEV` attempts to access the type of     │
│ this object via `getType()`, it hits the unreachable assertion in           │
│ `SCEV::getType()` for `scCouldNotCompute` objects.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s  │
│ Log:\n\nThe log shows that LoopIdiomRecognize is processing a countable     │
│ loop and crashes when trying to expand code for a strided store. The        │
│ debugger reveals that in `tryToReuseLCSSAPhi`, the `ExitSCEV` obtained from │
│ `SE.getSCEV(&PN)` for the PHI node `%phi` returns a `SCEVCouldNotCompute`   │
│ object. This happens because the PHI node has a pointer type with address   │
│ space 1, and SCEV cannot properly analyze it.\n\n3. Root Cause              │
│ Analysis:\n\nIn `ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp:1249`, the code calls          │
│ `SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV)` without checking if `ExitSCEV` is a valid    │
│ computable SCEV. When `SE.getSCEV(&PN)` returns a `SCEVCouldNotCompute`     │
│ object (which can happen for complex pointer types, especially with         │
│ non-zero address spaces), the subsequent `getMinusSCEV` call tries to       │
│ operate on this invalid object, leading to the crash when `getType()` is    │
│ called on it.\n\nThe issue is that the code assumes `ExitSCEV` will always  │
│ be a valid computable SCEV, but this is not guaranteed, especially for PHI  │
