  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe crash occurs when the
SCEVExpander tries to compute the difference between two SCEV expressions in
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi`, specifically calling `SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV)`. The
`ExitSCEV` is a `SCEVCouldNotCompute` object, which cannot be used in any SCEV
operations. When `getMinusSCEV` attempts to access the type of this object via
`getType()`, it hits the unreachable assertion in `SCEV::getType()` for
`scCouldNotCompute` objects.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe log shows that
LoopIdiomRecognize is processing a countable loop and crashes when trying to
expand code for a strided store. The debugger reveals that in
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi`, the `ExitSCEV` obtained from `SE.getSCEV(&PN)` for the
PHI node `%phi` returns a `SCEVCouldNotCompute` object. This happens because
the PHI node has a pointer type with address space 1, and SCEV cannot properly
analyze it.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nIn
`ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp:1249`, the code calls `SE.getMinusSCEV(S,
ExitSCEV)` without checking if `ExitSCEV` is a valid computable SCEV. When
`SE.getSCEV(&PN)` returns a `SCEVCouldNotCompute` object (which can happen for
complex pointer types, especially with non-zero address spaces), the subsequent
`getMinusSCEV` call tries to operate on this invalid object, leading to the
crash when `getType()` is called on it.\n\nThe issue is that the code assumes
`ExitSCEV` will always be a valid computable SCEV, but this is not guaranteed,
especially for PHI nodes with pointer types in non-default address
spaces.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to add a check in
`tryToReuseLCSSAPhi` to ensure that `ExitSCEV` is not a `SCEVCouldNotCompute`
object before attempting to use it in `getMinusSCEV`. This should be done right
after obtaining `ExitSCEV` from `SE.getSCEV(&PN)` and before the type
conversion logic.\n\nSpecifically, at line 1249 in
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp`, we need to add a guard
condition to skip processing when `ExitSCEV` is `SCEVCouldNotCompute`.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\n\nBy adding a check for `SCEVCouldNotCompute` before calling
`getMinusSCEV`, we prevent the crash and allow the expander to fall back to
other expansion strategies when SCEV analysis fails for complex pointer types.
This is a defensive programming fix that maintains the existing behavior for
valid cases while preventing the assertion failure for invalid cases.",
